y = Hitters$Salary

# remove the NAs:
y <-na.omit(y)

LASSO Regression

# Make a sequence of ridge regression models and plot:
fit.lasso = glmnet(X.model, y, alpha = 1)
plot(fit.lasso, xvar = "lambda")
grid(col = 2)

The trajectory plot tells us when each feature leaves the model as we increase the amount of penalization. The matrix “beta” tells us the estimated coefficients for each feature, at each different value of Lambda. Using this, we can isolate the last few variables that are left in the model.

fit.lasso$beta[,6]
## (Intercept)       AtBat        Hits       HmRun        Runs         RBI 
##  0.00000000  0.00000000  0.35506637  0.00000000  0.00000000  0.00000000

But such a model wouldn’t necessarily be the best model - we have decide which value of Lambda is the best choice. We can use cross validation to evaluate a large range of possible Lambda values. Then we can pick the value of the Lambda that results in the smallest cross validation error.

cv.lasso = cv.glmnet(X.model,y,alpha = 1)
plot(cv.lasso)

print(log(cv.lasso$lambda.min))
## [1] 1.07675
print(log(cv.lasso$lambda.1se))
## [1] 4.705066

Above is a Cross Validation plot for Lambda. Note that the true minimum is around log(Lambda)=1.1 but that variability due to sampling yields a 1-standard-error Lambda of around 4.7. This means that the most amount of regularization that we should accept corresponds to log(Lambda)=4.7. But any model with log(Lambda) less that 4.7 would yield comparable results in terms of cross validation error, so these would all be fine choices. (Worse, there is a fair amount of variability to the answer here simply to due to sampling variances, and different random seeds will yields different results. Let’s attribute this to the relatively tiny size of this data set.)

Now let’s pick our optimal model, and extract the features and coefficients for that model. These are the features that remain in the model at this particular value of Lambda.

lasso.best = glmnet(X.model, y, alpha=1, lambda=exp(1.1))
print(lasso.best$beta)

Short Answer

The bias-variance tradeoff describes the problem of overfitting and underfitting models. We can think of bias as a quantification of how well a model can fit a training data set. We can think of variance (in this context) as describing how much a model-fit might change upon being trained on new data points. Thus, variance is a quantification of how well a model can generalize to unseen data. Techniques which are more flexible tend to yields models with low bias yet high variance. Conversely, techniques which are less flexible tend to yield models with high bias and low variance.

In the case of regularized regression techniques, we use the regularization penalty to explicitly tune the model flexibility described above. With a large penalty parameter, our models becomes less flexible and incur high bias (though likely, low variance). With a small penatly parameter, our model remains flexible, but may have a tendecy to overfit. With reference to the LASSO trajectory plot above, a model with low pentalty (large log(Lambda)) will yield large magnitude coefficients, as the model is flexible enough to fit the training data very well (low bias). This would correspond to the left-most parts of the trajectory plots. As we increase the amount of penalty, the magnitudes of all coefficients tend to shrink down, making the model less flexible. The model naturally incurs some increases biad in this regime. At the extreme end, we have a very large penalty such that all the feature coefficients go to zero and the model is completely unable to fit the data (very high bias)
